00:01.380 --> 00:08.960
Okay, we have tape throwing on this end. Let's start off. How much time do we
have first? As much as you want. Oh, wow. Okay. We've got a rough cut at 4 o

00:08.960 --> 00:21.900
'clock, so we've got 55 minutes. That should be plenty of time. First, why don't
we start off with how did this project get started? Project got started, I was

00:21.900 --> 00:34.840
doing a half-hour situation comedy two years ago. I did the first two hours,
first four episodes of the sitcom, and was fired by Warner Brothers after the

00:34.840 --> 00:44.740
show became a hit in the grand show business tradition. So I went surfing, and I
was sitting on the beach the next day. It was just about two years ago, and

00:44.740 --> 00:56.060
decided to write a show that if it ever got on the air, I would watch it. That
was the basis of it, that I wanted to do something that I would watch, that I

00:56.060 --> 01:08.780
thought would be fun to see. And I started to kick around various elements of
different things that I had liked and different things that appealed to me and

01:08.780 --> 01:21.220
that I was interested in. And it was a combination of things, from the movie
Butch and Sundance and Star Wars and Raiders, which were all very hot. And my

01:21.220 --> 01:35.060
kids were heavily into Dungeons and Dragons and video games and stuff like that.
And I thought of doing a medieval version, something that looked medieval, a

01:35.060 --> 01:49.000
medieval version of Butch and Sundance, essentially. That is, characters who are
set in what appears to be an historical setting who have contemporary

01:49.000 --> 02:03.520
sensibilities. And that was the beginning of it. That was the first germ of what
became Greystone's Odyssey, which was the name of the show until last fall. And

02:03.520 --> 02:12.960
I took these various notions over to a friend of mine at CBS, who was in charge
of ordering scripts, and he responded to it right away. And what I did was then

02:12.960 --> 02:26.300
started to create a world. I created a world, a planet called Camerand, and set
all the action of this show on the continent of Aperans. Now, for my way of

02:26.300 --> 02:37.160
thinking, for all my staff and for everybody who's written it, the planet of
Camerand is Earth 500 million years in the future, post-technology. And it has

02:37.160 --> 02:49.340
returned to, through an evolutionary process, what we know of as historically as
the medieval times. But with twist. There are a lot of mutants. There is a

02:49.340 --> 03:02.820
holdover technology, which is controlled by the wizards, who have access to the
book, which is the source of knowledge and power. And that's basically what the

03:02.820 --> 03:13.580
framework is. Now, on the continent of Aperans, within that framework, there
is a war taking place between the forces of the North and the forces of the

03:13.580 --> 03:21.920
South. The forces of the North being represented by Prince Dirk Blackpool, the
bad guy, and the forces of the South being represented by Prince Eric Greystone.

03:22.900 --> 03:24.760
That's essentially what happened.

03:28.100 --> 03:28.800
Okay.

03:31.660 --> 03:46.440
How far have you gotten into production? We shot a pilot last year. CBS saw that
and ordered seven additional episodes. I completed filming the eighth episode

03:46.440 --> 03:57.060
about two weeks ago, and we're in post-production now. Okay. Then it's
pretty well along. Do you have any projected air date? We will go on the air

03:57.060 --> 04:11.200
Saturday, March the 5th at 8 o'clock on CBS. Yes. Okay. I thought I saw
something. CBS runs the gizmos where they say, you know, here's what's coming

04:11.200 --> 04:21.400
next month. And I thought I saw something that dealt with your program on there,
but it was like a two-second micro blitz of a guy with a sword that was glowing,

04:21.540 --> 04:27.920
and he whooped around, and then it was off. It's amazing that you actually saw
that. I saw it, too. I was skiing last week. I had no idea they were going to do

04:27.920 --> 04:45.660
that. There are two little clips, probably, it's almost subliminal, from an
episode called The Rescue, where the wizard Vector, well, this shows everything.

04:45.840 --> 04:56.540
It's so complicated. Prince Eric Greystone is hanging, dangling at the end of a
chain over a slime pit, which contains a slime monster. And the wizard Vector

04:56.540 --> 05:05.440
sends this laser beam to the top of the chain, which heats the chain, and the
heat begins to descend until it touches his hands, and he has to let go and fall

05:05.440 --> 05:14.540
into the pit. You saw the casting of that beam and the slow-motion shot of
Greystone falling towards the water.

05:17.400 --> 05:27.000
I knew it wasn't from any show that I had seen previously, and I knew it wasn't
a cut from Star Wars, which CBS is hoping to show, so I knew it probably had to

05:27.000 --> 05:35.640
be your show. Well, that's very observant of you. Yeah, this show does not look
like anything you have ever seen on television. I guarantee you that. It is

05:35.640 --> 05:45.520
very, very different. It's quite an adventure. Why don't you go into explaining
a little bit of what the differences are? Well, everything is different. First

05:45.520 --> 05:52.820
of all, it breaks all the rules. You're not supposed to do period pieces on
television. They don't work. Well, this isn't really a period piece, but it

05:52.820 --> 06:08.340
looks like one when you first see it. It's heavily costumed, the show is. It
deals with fantasy, which outside of Star Trek has not been very successful.

06:09.600 --> 06:19.260
There's a lot of science fiction overtones to it. It is episodic,

06:19.340 --> 06:33.240
but it's also a serial in the way that MASH is. You know, the war is the
overriding thing, so each episode doesn't wrap up a problem neatly. It is shot

06:33.240 --> 06:45.680
with fog filters and half corals, which gives it a very storybook look. Nothing
else on television does that. Everything about it is different. I just, it's

06:45.680 --> 06:52.360
very hard to explain. There's humor in it, and yet people die. There are no
jokes, but it's very funny.

06:57.440 --> 07:07.040
I can't think of anything that even compares to it. Did I read correctly that
you made some references to MASH? Are there some of the writers from MASH

07:07.040 --> 07:21.940
working on the show? I produced MASH in 1975-76 along with Burt Metcalf and Alan
Katz, and I did 26 episodes of it. Nobody else on my staff worked on MASH. Okay,

07:22.040 --> 07:31.460
that's where I remember seeing your name. I'm a big MASH fan. Uh-huh. Okay. You
mentioned something about the effects. Does the show have quite a bit of special

07:31.460 --> 07:42.860
effects in it then? Yeah. One of the episodes, just looking at it today, called
The Kidnap, has a special effect in every scene. It's an enormous amount of

07:42.860 --> 08:00.760
special effects, matte work, beam splitters, opticals, rotoscoping, a lot of it.
It's a very, very expensive endeavor. I was just thinking, it must be pretty

08:00.760 --> 08:14.340
expensive to produce then. It's enormously expensive. It's the most expensive
series that CBS has ever commissioned. It's a gamble. They should be commended

08:14.340 --> 08:21.940
for taking this gamble. I mean, for all the people who are fantasy and science
fiction fans, they should write a thank you note to CBS, because I don't know

08:21.940 --> 08:34.020
anybody else in television who would have attempted this. Yeah. Yeah, after ABC
had a lot of hopes for Battlestar Galactica, if you remember when that came on.

08:34.120 --> 08:43.040
Yeah. And the effects were just fantastic, but the writing just kind of fell
off, and the show didn't hold up from the writing end of it. Yeah, you've got to

08:43.040 --> 08:54.280
start with solid scripts, solid characters, and hope that people respond to that
first. Because as far as dazzling people with special effects, you know, you go

08:54.280 --> 09:04.960
to the movies and you're going to see $20 million special effects. So we're not
going to show anything that hasn't been seen before in films, but we have

09:04.960 --> 09:17.620
characters that no one's ever seen before in an interesting situation, I think.
The classic situation, it's good against evil. Yeah, I'm a big fan of fantasy

09:17.620 --> 09:21.580
myself. Read a lot. Play Dungeons and Dragons. Oh, her.

09:26.500 --> 09:38.620
But what, if you can, what is the market that you're aiming at? George Lucas
once said that Star Wars was designed for kids or anybody who's ever been one.

09:38.820 --> 09:49.380
You know, I think that's the market that I want. They're putting it on at 8 o
'clock, so it's a highly visual show, so hopefully it'll attract a young

09:49.380 --> 10:03.020
audience. But I think young adults and even not-so-young adults will respond to
it because it can be viewed on different levels. When you have as broad a canvas

10:03.020 --> 10:18.400
as we have, you have the possibility, the opportunity to do parables. And
everything is structured on various levels. You can interpret the stories, the

10:18.400 --> 10:27.180
lines, on a sophisticated adult level, or you can just go straight ahead with
the story and look at the monsters and the power swords.

10:30.220 --> 10:38.720
I think it will appeal to a lot of people, or it will appeal to no one. This
show is either a rocket or a bomb. One or the other. It's not in between. I

10:38.720 --> 10:53.900
happen to like it. Okay. Yeah, I have, if I can express my own personal opinion
here, I really have hoped for a fantasy or science fiction show, you know, a

10:53.900 --> 11:02.080
really good one to come on, and they seem to have been lacking. Do you have any
opinions as to why that might be? Yeah, everything out here is done by

11:02.080 --> 11:13.900
committee. Once you start with an idea, you can have a pure idea, a great idea.
And you take it to one of the networks and you pitch it to a person at a

11:13.900 --> 11:23.480
network, and that person makes changes along with his assistants, and they all
make changes because it's their money in the end. And then his boss will make

11:23.480 --> 11:33.220
changes, and then his boss will make changes. And then you go into, if you're
working with a studio like I am, the studio will request changes. Actors then

11:33.220 --> 11:45.120
request changes. Directors make changes, and it never stops. There's always
groups of people who have input, and the net effect is you end up with a watered

11:45.120 --> 11:56.120
-down property. You know, I see things on the air, and I say, my God, that's a
great idea, but the execution is so bad. And then I remember how this town works

11:56.120 --> 12:07.600
and realize why very few things come through with clarity and purity, and it's
because of interference. With Wizards and Warriors, I was extraordinarily

12:07.600 --> 12:18.840
fortunate in the gentleman at CVS that I first told the idea to said, go ahead.
Within 30 seconds, it was an incredible meeting, and all his assistants were

12:18.840 --> 12:31.140
dumbfounded. He understood it, and he has shepherded the project. He shares the
vision of the project with me. His name is Kim LaMasters, incidentally. And he

12:31.140 --> 12:40.560
has shepherded it through all this complicated process of writing and making
pilots and then writing episodes and making them, and all the pitfalls have been

12:40.560 --> 12:55.880
avoided. The show is exactly as I conceived it initially that day on the beach,
maybe better. And that's the first time I've ever experienced that sort of thing

12:55.880 --> 13:07.460
in this business. Yeah, I know how difficult that must have been because of the
convoluted process that things get from the idea stage to the actual finished

13:07.460 --> 13:12.060
product. We managed to avoid all of it. All right.

13:17.980 --> 13:29.660
Did I understand you that you do some or all or a lot of the writing? I wrote,
let's see, I wrote four of the eight shows. The co-executive producer, Judith

13:29.660 --> 13:41.340
Allison, wrote one. A fellow named Bill Richmond wrote two of them. A fellow
named Robert Earle wrote one. And those are the eight that are going on here.

13:42.200 --> 13:57.100
Okay. Could you give me a brief rundown of how the script writing process goes?
Yes. When we're working in production and I have a staff, as I did starting last

13:57.100 --> 14:08.180
July, there's me, Judith Allison, Bill Richmond, Robert Earle, and another
wonderful writer named Paul Edwards. We all get in a room and sit down and start

14:08.180 --> 14:17.240
to talk about stories, possible stories. And when we seize on an idea that
everybody agrees on, we start to work out the story, break it down into four

14:17.240 --> 14:27.140
acts, and then take one scene at a time. The first scene is this, the second
scene is this, so on and so forth. The end of the first act is this.

14:27.140 --> 14:35.220
All the way through it until we have a completed story. And somebody
takes notes. I get those notes. I get on the phone with the network, in this

14:35.220 --> 14:44.500
case CBS, and tell them the story. If they accept the story, we then go ahead to
first draft, which is one individual writer will go ahead and write a complete

14:44.500 --> 14:55.980
first draft. We then take the first draft and in-house sit down and read it out
loud. We split up the parts. Everybody will play a character. And we actually do

14:55.980 --> 15:07.900
the play, as it were, in my office here. That's a system that Gene Reynolds
instituted and maybe initiated on MASH. And I found it to be very successful

15:07.900 --> 15:14.440
because then you're not hearing these lines for the first time and you don't
have an actor say, my God, I can't say that. It's awful. Because you've already

15:14.440 --> 15:25.820
said it. The answer can always be, well, I can say it if you can't. And we do it
that way. And the result of that meeting becomes the second draft, which is then

15:25.820 --> 15:38.580
sent to the network for their comments, suggested changes, and standards and
practices, obviously, will take out anything that they find objectionable or ask

15:38.580 --> 15:44.600
us to take it out. A lot of arguments there. And that's basically how it works
when you're in production.

