19:00.780 --> 19:11.780
What do you think are the possibilities for a run on the show? Like I said, it's
a rocket or a bomb. I don't know. So, it's very different. It's unique. You

19:11.780 --> 19:18.860
know, it's all the things that people say television isn't. I don't know if
anybody's going to like it. You know, you get tunnel vision, at least I do, when

19:18.860 --> 19:29.500
I get involved in a project this deeply. It's been two years now. You lose
objectivity. And the best you can do is cling to your initial idea and the

19:29.500 --> 19:38.620
excitement that that idea generated and try and stay true to that. Whether or
not anybody else will like it, I absolutely don't know. But if they do, it'll be

19:38.620 --> 19:51.140
in large numbers. But if they don't, you'll never hear of me again. Well, I
certainly hope that's not true. No, that's not true. Let's see. I think I've

19:51.140 --> 19:57.140
basically covered all the questions that I wrote down here. Is there anything
else that you would have to say about it?

20:00.820 --> 20:10.960
I don't know. You know, it's really even difficult for me to talk about this
show because it is an amalgam of so many different things. It has become

20:10.960 --> 20:18.840
something of its own, you know. So, it's very exciting. It's fun. And it's fast.

20:22.880 --> 20:33.080
I just hope a lot of people watch it. Okay, right. I can tell you that I'll be
glued to my tube with my videotape recorder doing March the 5th. So will I.

20:34.280 --> 20:41.040
You'll get to see it a couple hours before I do, though. Oh, yeah, that's right.
We're a couple hours ahead of y'all there. But you will have seen it previous to

20:41.040 --> 20:55.660
that, I'm sure, a few times. Yeah, I've seen one of the shows 106 times
yesterday. Oh, my Lord. The pilot, which we, you know, in the pilot it was a

20:55.660 --> 21:05.760
completed story, a non-completed story. We had an open ending on it as to
whether or not the princess was rescued. That's what makes for good pilots.

21:05.880 --> 21:15.020
People want to see the next one. So we had to go back and reshoot the end of it
so we would have a complete episode. And it seems like I've been working on that

21:15.020 --> 21:22.040
one forever. I mean, I wrote it two years ago, and I'm still working on it. As a
matter of fact, we're still going to continue to work on it. We're doing some

21:22.040 --> 21:31.400
voiceover work on it next week. We're going to start to live with these things.
They become a part of your life. One of the challenges, one thing that I found

21:31.400 --> 21:44.000
interesting in writing all these episodes was one of these self-imposed rules. I
wanted the heroes at every act break, which is four times an hour, to be in a

21:44.000 --> 21:54.940
situation where they could not possibly survive. And then after the act break,
find a way to have them survive. And we've managed to do that, but I'll tell

21:54.940 --> 22:06.320
you, that's a challenge. You start out trying to think of a situation that
somebody cannot get out of and then work backwards. That was a major time

22:06.320 --> 22:06.760
consumer.

22:09.580 --> 22:20.920
The cliffhanger. Yes, indeed. The cliffhanger. These guys run into a lot of
problems. There are snake-faced people, not only the wizards, but all these

22:20.920 --> 22:31.900
mutants and monsters running around. And it's a rough life in Camarand. Sounds
like it. I wonder if they need all those special effects to get out of the hole.

22:37.980 --> 22:41.940
When the show hits the air, you know how the...

22:44.780 --> 22:53.680
I can't think of a good way to ask this one. When the show becomes popular, when
it hits the air and people go, oh, wow, you know, this new show was on. It's got

22:53.680 --> 23:05.400
all this fantasy, fantastic stuff on it. What do you think the general public is
going to gravitate toward first? The people. No question about it. In

23:05.400 --> 23:15.920
television, you're selling people. That's what it is. That's why certain actors
endure, you know, because they're comfortable to have in your living room. There

23:15.920 --> 23:26.400
are certain television personalities, if you will, you know, like Bill Bixby and
James Garner and those people who go from one hit series to another. That's the

23:26.400 --> 23:34.860
first thing that people respond to, is the people. And we have a varied and
interesting group.

23:37.520 --> 23:44.220
After that, it's the writing. It's the question of the stories. Are the stories
engrossing? Do they hold your attention? Do you get bored? Do you go to sleep?

23:44.340 --> 23:53.720
Do you go to the refrigerator or the bathroom? You have to be able to hold
people and entertain them. That's what this is all about. You know, it's a giant

23:53.720 --> 23:58.280
game, but we're trying to entertain people. Starting with me.

24:03.740 --> 24:06.760
Very good. All right.

24:11.640 --> 24:19.800
So this is probably a pretty dumb question, but I can ask it anyway. How do you
know when you've got a good story idea?

24:23.500 --> 24:37.420
Well, it fulfills certain requirements. You know it when you hear it, is all I
can tell you after doing this for 14 years. This year. It's a story that grabs

24:37.420 --> 24:50.120
your attention. You start with one line, usually, with one sentence. You know,
what if there was a nuclear device planted in the castle? Well, that's one of

24:50.120 --> 25:02.660
the scripts that we did. We started with a basic sentence. And that was
interesting to me, that you could have some huge explosive device hidden in the

25:02.660 --> 25:12.300
good guy's castle that they can't find. And the ramifications of that, you know,
that can't be turned off. You can't stop it unless you get this key that's in a

25:12.300 --> 25:20.480
place that's filled where one false move is a certain death. So the heroes
obviously have to go and get the key and then get back in time to shut the thing

25:20.480 --> 25:37.860
off. You just know it. I mean, that was instantly a story that I wanted to do. I
think a good story idea begs the question, what happens then? That's when you

25:37.860 --> 25:38.840
know you have a good story.

25:41.980 --> 25:43.900
Okay, very good and very interesting.

